00:47:46,700 --> 00:47:59,667
My name is Dr. Peter Cushing, I'm one of the assistant superintendents at the Medford public schools here with my co chair of the McGlynn redesign committee, she named Peloquin Medford resident.

476
00:48:01,268 --> 00:48:06,532
And I just want to take a moment to thank everybody for having us this evening to hear our presentation.

477
00:48:07,352 --> 00:48:12,216
For those of you who may remember, it was prior to the pandemic.

478
00:48:12,336 --> 00:48:14,978
So a lot of people forget those times.

479
00:48:16,279 --> 00:48:26,245
Unfortunately, the CPC awarded us $40,000 to do a design study because we were looking to resurface with poured in place surface

480
00:48:28,027 --> 00:48:31,190
Two, nope, let me just think about this for a second.

481
00:48:31,651 --> 00:48:38,098
Two of the playgrounds, because the Roberts had already been done, at the Brooks and the Missittuck Elementary School.

482
00:48:39,452 --> 00:48:43,654
We replaced several play elements that were damaged and beyond their useful life.

483
00:48:44,375 --> 00:48:49,297
And then we were also planning to look at the McGlynn playground.

484
00:48:49,357 --> 00:48:54,960
The McGlynn playground is approximately 25,000 square feet in size.

485
00:48:55,360 --> 00:49:06,306
And currently the design from the early 2000s has about the entire space covered in poured in place.

486
00:49:07,708 --> 00:49:09,929
The Port in Place is definitely at the end of its life.

487
00:49:10,229 --> 00:49:12,010
And so we were looking to replace that.

488
00:49:12,150 --> 00:49:16,212
The cost estimates on that were north of $500,000.

489
00:49:17,152 --> 00:49:26,256
So that really triggered in us to really look at like, if we're gonna spend this much on Port in Place, what's the overall state of the playground?

490
00:49:27,557 --> 00:49:33,820
That has really triggered a really thoughtful and intentional approach to looking at our playgrounds within the Medford Public Schools.

491
00:49:35,212 --> 00:49:58,690
And in looking at the McGlynn Playground, we have conducted inspections, head drop tests, and have formed the committee that's now been working for about six months or so to really examine how we can make this a universally accessible playground, give kids real value in play.

492
00:49:58,730 --> 00:50:01,693
The current structure, it looks really good from afar,

493
00:50:02,393 --> 00:50:13,137
but it really has no play value other than kids running up and down and utilizing the slides, but it has extraordinarily limited play value.

494
00:50:13,477 --> 00:50:15,758
I shouldn't say no play value, but limited play value.

495
00:50:17,939 --> 00:50:21,000
And if we could move to the next slide, I would appreciate that.

496
00:50:22,437 --> 00:50:31,241
So our project goals as a committee were number one, to make sure it is fun, safe, accessible, and reflects the identity of the students.

497
00:50:32,101 --> 00:50:43,767
A considerable amount of work has been done by Shanine and by our partners at Copley-Wolf Design Group to get

498
00:50:44,787 --> 00:50:56,762
student input on this to listen to faculty and staff and to design a world class playground that will meet the needs of the students of Medford for years to come.

499
00:50:57,103 --> 00:50:59,706
So first we're going to meet the needs of the McGlynn school.

500
00:51:00,682 --> 00:51:02,303
If face construction is required.

501
00:51:03,223 --> 00:51:06,584
We're offering a range of challenges for all users.

502
00:51:07,504 --> 00:51:14,927
We're considering wider benefit to the broader community and something that can be maintained within the school and city's resources.

503
00:51:15,247 --> 00:51:25,391
One of the things that we've really noticed is that we need to do a better job making sure that we are properly inspecting and maintaining our playgrounds within the meant for public schools.

504
00:51:26,337 --> 00:51:30,099
I'd like to now turn the presentation over to Shanine for the next few slides.

505
00:51:30,799 --> 00:51:31,119
Thank you.

506
00:51:32,200 --> 00:51:39,343
Hi, it's been a pleasure working on this and and really making sure that we get student feedback in particular on this.

507
00:51:39,604 --> 00:51:42,905
And we've heard really amazing things from the students, including like.

508
00:51:42,925 --> 00:51:48,368
5th graders, including the boys were like, we want places to pretend that we're.

509
00:51:48,733 --> 00:51:52,355
Playing restaurant, we want drive-up windows and table service.

510
00:51:52,415 --> 00:51:54,676
And we want places to pretend that we're flying.

511
00:51:54,716 --> 00:52:01,400
And these are the older kids that I think that, as adults, we assume they're just going to play football on the side.

512
00:52:01,480 --> 00:52:04,602
But they really want opportunities for lots of different kinds of play.

513
00:52:05,182 --> 00:52:10,905
This is the current schematic of the program.

